Use `getBoundingBox()` which recalculates from all bones each call:

```typescript
const armature = ccs.Armature.create('hero');
armature.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(armature);
armature.animation.play('idle', -1, -1);

// Get bounding box
const box: cc.Rect = armature.getBoundingBox();
cc.log('x:', box.x, 'y:', box.y, 'w:', box.width, 'h:', box.height);

// Use for broad-phase collision detection
function checkCollision(armA: ccs.Armature, armB: ccs.Armature): boolean {
    const boxA = armA.getBoundingBox();
    const boxB = armB.getBoundingBox();
    return cc.rectOverlapsRect(boxA, boxB);
}
```

Note: `getBoundingBox()` recalculates from all bones on every call, so it reflects the current animation pose. This can be expensive if called frequently — cache the result per frame if needed.

These four layout types control how child widgets are positioned inside a `ccui.Layout`:

**`ABSOLUTE` (default)** — Free positioning. You set each child's position manually with `setPosition()`. No automatic arrangement.

**`LINEAR_HORIZONTAL`** — Children flow left to right. Order is determined by `addChild` order. Use `ccui.LinearLayoutParameter` for gravity and margins:
```typescript
layout.setLayoutType(ccui.Layout.LINEAR_HORIZONTAL);
```

**`LINEAR_VERTICAL`** — Children flow top to bottom. Same parameter system as horizontal:
```typescript
layout.setLayoutType(ccui.Layout.LINEAR_VERTICAL);
const param = new ccui.LinearLayoutParameter();
param.setGravity(ccui.LinearLayoutParameter.CENTER_HORIZONTAL);
param.setMargin(new ccui.Margin(0, 10, 0, 0));
child.setLayoutParameter(param);
```

**`RELATIVE`** — Children are positioned relative to the parent or sibling widgets. Uses `ccui.RelativeLayoutParameter`:
```typescript
layout.setLayoutType(ccui.Layout.RELATIVE);
const rel = new ccui.RelativeLayoutParameter();
rel.setAlign(ccui.RelativeLayoutParameter.PARENT_TOP_LEFT);
rel.setRelativeName('myWidget');
child.setLayoutParameter(rel);
```

For linear and relative layouts, call `layout.forceDoLayout()` after adding children to trigger positioning.

