btn.setSizePercent(cc.p(0.5, 0.1)); // 50% width, 10% height
btn.setPositionType(ccui.Widget.POSITION_PERCENT);
btn.setPositionPercent(cc.p(0.5, 0.8)); // centered at 50% x, 80% y
parentLayout.addChild(btn);
```

Percentage sizes are fractions (0-1) of the parent's dimensions.

```typescript
// Quadratic Bezier — 1 control point
drawQuadBezier(
    origin: cc.Point,
    control: cc.Point,
    destination: cc.Point,
    segments: number,
    lineWidth: number,
    color?: cc.Color
): void

// Cubic Bezier — 2 control points
drawCubicBezier(
    origin: cc.Point,
    control1: cc.Point,
    control2: cc.Point,
    destination: cc.Point,
    segments: number,
    lineWidth: number,
    color?: cc.Color
): void
```

Both return `void`. The key difference is quadratic uses one `control` point for simple arcs, while cubic uses `control1` and `control2` for more complex S-shaped curves.

Example:
```typescript
const draw: cc.DrawNode = new cc.DrawNode();
this.addChild(draw);

// Quadratic (3 points)
draw.drawQuadBezier(
    cc.p(0, 0), cc.p(100, 200), cc.p(200, 0),
    30, 2, cc.color(255, 0, 0, 255)
);

// Cubic (4 points)
draw.drawCubicBezier(
    cc.p(0, 0), cc.p(50, 200), cc.p(150, -100), cc.p(200, 100),
    30, 2, cc.color(0, 0, 255, 255)
);
```

