instruction:
Find and fix the bug in this touch listener code:

```typescript
class ButtonLayer extends cc.Layer {
    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        cc.eventManager.addListener({
            event: cc.EventListener.TOUCH_ONE_BY_ONE,
            swallowTouches: true,
            onTouchBegan: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event) => {
                cc.log('Touch started');
            },
            onTouchEnded: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event) => {
                cc.log('Button tapped!');
            }
        }, this);
    }
}
```

output:
The bug is that `onTouchBegan` does not return `true`. In Cocos2d-x, `onTouchBegan` must return `true` to claim the touch; otherwise `onTouchMoved`, `onTouchEnded`, and `onTouchCancelled` will never fire.

Fixed code:
```typescript
class ButtonLayer extends cc.Layer {
    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        cc.eventManager.addListener({
            event: cc.EventListener.TOUCH_ONE_BY_ONE,
            swallowTouches: true,
            onTouchBegan: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event): boolean => {
                cc.log('Touch started');
                return true; // FIX: must return true to receive onTouchEnded
            },
            onTouchEnded: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event): void => {
                cc.log('Button tapped!');
            }
        }, this);
    }
}
```

Without `return true`, the touch is not claimed and all subsequent callbacks for that touch are skipped. This is one of the most common bugs with Cocos2d-x touch handling.

Use removeAllActionsFromTarget to stop and remove every action running on a node:

```typescript
const mgr = cc.director.getActionManager();
mgr.removeAllActionsFromTarget(mySprite, true);
```

The second param (forceDelete) when true removes even locked actions. Common cleanup pattern:

```typescript
class Enemy extends cc.Sprite {
    destroy(): void {
        const mgr = cc.director.getActionManager();
        mgr.removeAllActionsFromTarget(this, true);
        this.removeFromParent();
    }
}

// Batch cleanup
function cleanupAll(nodes: cc.Node[]): void {
    const mgr = cc.director.getActionManager();
    for (const node of nodes) {
        mgr.removeAllActionsFromTarget(node, true);
        node.removeFromParent();
    }
}
```

This is the ActionManager equivalent of `node.stopAllActions()`. Use the manager directly when you need to clean up nodes you do not have direct references to.

